# How to Use Alert Dialogs with Shadcn UI (`alert-dialog.tsx`)

## Context

We use the [Shadcn UI Alert Dialog](https://ui.shadcn.com/docs/components/alert-dialog) component to display important modal dialogs that require user confirmation or action.  
The implementation is located in `src/components/ui/alert-dialog.tsx` and is based on Radix UI primitives, styled with Tailwind and Shadcn conventions.

## Installation

To add the Alert Dialog component to your project, run:

```bash
pnpm dlx shadcn@latest add alert-dialog
```

## Usage

Import the required components from your UI library:

```tsx
import {
  AlertDialog,
  AlertDialogTrigger,
  AlertDialogContent,
  AlertDialogHeader,
  AlertDialogTitle,
  AlertDialogDescription,
  AlertDialogFooter,
  AlertDialogAction,
  AlertDialogCancel,
} from "@/components/ui/alert-dialog";
```

Wrap your content with the `AlertDialog` component and use the provided subcomponents to structure your dialog:

```tsx
<AlertDialog>
  <AlertDialogTrigger>
    <Button>Open Dialog</Button>
  </AlertDialogTrigger>
  <AlertDialogContent>
    <AlertDialogHeader>
      <AlertDialogTitle>Are you absolutely sure?</AlertDialogTitle>
      <AlertDialogDescription>
        This action cannot be undone. This will permanently delete your account and remove your data from our servers.
      </AlertDialogDescription>
    </AlertDialogHeader>
    <AlertDialogFooter>
      <AlertDialogCancel>Cancel</AlertDialogCancel>
      <AlertDialogAction variant="destructive">Continue</AlertDialogAction>
    </AlertDialogFooter>
  </AlertDialogContent>
</AlertDialog>
```

## Features

- **Accessible**: Built on top of Radix UI primitives for accessibility.
- **Customizable**: Use the `variant` prop on `AlertDialogAction` for different button styles (e.g., `"default"`, `"destructive"`, `"outline"`).
- **Composable**: All subcomponents (`Header`, `Title`, `Description`, `Footer`, `Action`, `Cancel`) are available for flexible dialog layouts.
- **Client Component**: The dialog is a client-side component and should be used in client-rendered parts of your app.

## Best Practices

- Use `AlertDialog` for actions that are destructive or require explicit user confirmation.
- Always provide both a cancel and a confirm action for clarity.
- Keep dialog content concise and clear.

